{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491284"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:40:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:40:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"903"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/903"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.03,0.05,0.02,0.9]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109034"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/903"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91400"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"175"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11236"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37878"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40717"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109034"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after falling from a ladder and landing on his back. He complains of dull pain in the lumbar region. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His medications include perindopril and metformin. He is a retired builder with no recent travel history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with pulse rate 78/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is mild generalised lower back tenderness with superficial abrasions. Neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT chest, abdomen and pelvis reveals a 6.2 cm infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm with intraluminal thrombus (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and discharge","Surveillance ultrasound in six months","Commence anticoagulation therapy","Repeat contrast-enhanced CT abdomen","Urgent vascular surgical referral"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an incidentally discovered 6.2 cm abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) on CT imaging performed for trauma assessment. The CT shows intraluminal thrombus occupying approximately one-quarter of the aneurysmal sac. Given the size of this aneurysm, immediate specialist assessment is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent vascular surgical referral\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. AAAs greater than 55 mm diameter have a significantly increased risk of rupture (approximately 10-20% per year) vs 0.3-0.8% for AAA less than 55 mm, and require consideration for elective repair. The vascular surgeon will assess the patient\u0027s fitness for intervention and discuss options including open surgical repair or endovascular aneurysm repair (EVAR).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and discharge\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and dangerous given the size of this aneurysm. The rupture risk is substantial, and the patient requires specialist assessment and likely intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurveillance ultrasound in six months\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate for an aneurysm of this size. While smaller aneurysms (25-54 mm) are managed with surveillance at varying intervals, aneurysms greater than 55 mm require urgent specialist referral rather than routine surveillance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence anticoagulation therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated and could potentially be harmful. Anticoagulation does not reduce aneurysm expansion or rupture risk and may increase bleeding complications if rupture occurs. Standard cardiovascular risk reduction with antiplatelet therapy, statins and blood pressure control is appropriate, but anticoagulation has no role.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat contrast-enhanced CT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary as the diagnosis has already been established. The current imaging provides sufficient information for surgical planning. Additional contrast exposure should be avoided unless specifically requested by the vascular team for operative planning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe indications for elective AAA repair include diameter greater than 55 mm, rapid expansion (greater than 1 cm per year), or symptomatic aneurysm. This patient meets the size criteria and requires urgent specialist assessment to plan definitive management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abdominal aortic aneurysms greater than 55 mm diameter require urgent vascular surgical referral due to high rupture risk.","Incidental discovery of large AAA requires immediate management planning regardless of symptoms.","Surveillance intervals for AAA depend on size and may be ceased when operative management becomes unsuitable such as in very co-morbid or elderly patients"],"references":["Kent KC. Abdominal Aortic Aneurysms. N Engl J Med 2014;371:2101-08. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25427112/","Watanabe S, Usui M, Egi K, Takazawa K. Impending rupture of abdominal aortic aneurysm due to apixaban use. J Cardiol Cases. 2020;23(5):221-223. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8103311/","ESVS 2024 Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysm. In: European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://esvs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/ESVS-2024-AAA-Guidelines.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91400"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"903"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14921"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14921"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5b74db77-05de-4a6c-a8cb-a0e1c6984249.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5b74db77-05de-4a6c-a8cb-a0e1c6984249.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91400"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T15:05:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T15:42:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"903"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109034"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"i